      "ESSeqNum": 0,
      "FacilityID": 1000109766,
      "SummaryText": "Two chlorine evaporation systems are fed liquid chlorine from 2000 pound containers and each system feeds gaseous chlorine to an aluminum furnace.  The gaseous chlorine is injected into a molten aluminum pump and reacts with magnesium impurity to refine the aluminum.  The Chlorine Building can house up to eight 1-ton chlorine cylinders at a time. \n\nAccidental Release Prevention and Emergency Response Policies:\nState Metal Industries' policy is to comply with all applicable rules and regulations including OSHA Process Safety Management, EPA Accidental Release Prevention and New Jersey Toxic Catastrophe Prevention Act.  The chlorine system and procedures are based on recommendations of the Chlorine Institute.\n\nGeneral Accidental Release Prevention Program and Chemical-Specific Prevention Steps:\nIn addition to the requirements of EPA (40 CFR 68) and OSHA PSM (29 CFR 1910.119), State Metal Industries has been covered by New Jersey's Toxic Catastrophe Prevention Act regulations (Title 7 NJAC Chapter 31) since 1987.  All systems and procedures are based on Chlorine Institute recommendations to ensure safe operation.  Chlorine sensors and an alarm system with both local alarms and a connection to an alarm monitoring company warn of a chlorine leak in the Chlorine Building or at the furnaces, to facilitate rapid emergency response.  An annual audit of all aspects of the RMP program, including preventive maintenance and emergency response, is conducted.\n\nFive-Year Accident History:\nThere were leaks of chlorine on 1/21/21 and 8/9/21.  Incident investigations were conducted, and corrective and preventive actions were identified and completed.  The first evaporator system has operated since 1986 and the second system since 1994, and there have never been any releases with offsite consequences.\n\nEmergency Response Program:\nIn case of a chlorine leak the Chlorine Building is vented to the plant air pollution control system for dilution, some neutralization with lime, and dispersa"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000109766,
      "SummaryText": "l from a stack. The facility has an emergency response team on site and drills annually.  The Emergency Response Plan (i.e. employee evacuation) also includes annual refresher training and a full-scale drill.   The site coordinators are trained to contact the Camden Fire Department (911), Camden City LEPC, NJ DEP and the National Response Center as appropriate.\n\nPlanned Changes to Improve Safety:\nThe Risk Management Program at State Metal Industries is a mature program that has been implemented since 1987 with continual improvements.  An improvement which is currently being reviewed for feasibility is possibly piping any potential discharge from the evaporator pressure relief valves to a safer location (they would currently discharge inside the Chlorine Building). Management remains open to any practical equipment or procedures that will improve safety.\n\n5/13/24 Correction: Based on feedback, discussion and agreement with David Dovedytis of NJDEP, the release quantity for the Worst Case Release Scenario was corrected to 2000 lb, which is the quantity contained in one chlorine container.  Similarly, the hole diameter used in RMP*Comp to calculate the release rate for the Alternative Release Scenario was corrected to 11/32\", which is the diameter of the fusible portion of the fusible plug in a chlorine container."
    }
